issue.title: Divergence between PushIO and Model implementations
issue.body:
The following code demonstrates a difference between the PushIO and Model implementations:

```Haskell
{-# LANGUAGE ScopedTypeVariables #-}

import Data.Maybe
import qualified Reactive.Banana.Implementation as PushIO
import Reactive.Banana.Incremental
import Reactive.Banana.Model as Model

data Incoming = IncomingA | IncomingB deriving (Show)

data Outgoing = Outgoing deriving (Show)

filterJust :: FRP f => Event f (Maybe a) -> Event f a
filterJust = fmap fromJust . filterE isJust

f :: forall f. FRP f => Event f Incoming -> Event f Outgoing
f incoming = outgoing
  where
    incomingA :: Event f ()
    incomingA =
      filterJust
      $
      (\x -> case x of
          IncomingA -> Just ()
          _ -> Nothing
      )
      <$>
      incoming

    incomingB :: Event f ()
    incomingB =
      filterJust
      $
      (\x -> case x of
          IncomingB -> Just ()
          _ -> Nothing
      )
      <$>
      incoming
      
    discrete = accumD () (id <$ incomingB)

    outgoing = Outgoing <$ (changes discrete)

main1 = return (Model.interpret f [IncomingA,IncomingB]) >>= print
main2 = (PushIO.interpret f [IncomingA,IncomingB]) >>= print

-- Output: Prelude.last: empty list
-- main = main1

-- Output: [[],[Outgoing]]
-- main = main2
```

When the Model implementation is used, the program crashes. When the PushIO implementation is used, it runs just fine and produces the correct answer.

issue.body:
Currently, minions will always accept a master pubkey at first connect (provided it verifies the master has the correct private). I'd like to have at least configurably a mode where minion will not accept an unknown master.

Possibly a new minion config param "trust_mode" or so -- "open" (like open_mode True) "store" (same as now, default?) "strict" (key must be known). If both open_mode and trust_mode...take the more restrictive is probably The Right Thing

Motivation would be running a system in an untrusted network (something like amazon ec2). Getting master pub key in place would probably be outside the scope of salt though it would be possible to extend for minions something like what masters do to verify minion pubkeys...

- minion connects but doesn't know master
- wait, check for (local) acceptance of master key, wait, etc

Hopefully even re-use the 'retry' logic...haven't checked that yet

salt-key could be extended to "master" and "minion" modes for accepting master keys

I'm starting to work on this, comments, criticisms gladly taken

issue.title: Devise is ApplicationController-centric to a fault
issue.body:
It used to be that Rails programmers wrote their application as a single Rails program. These days, many of us are writing our applications as collections of multiple engines, with nothing in the central application except what is necessary to load those engines and mount their routes. Devise fails that sort of application in multiple ways. So many ways that it's probably time for the Devise documentation to bear a warning that it doesn't work at present to use Devise from engines.

Devise internals depend on `ApplicationController`, and Devise installs its methods and helpers in `ApplicationController`. Engine-centric applications are unlikely to contain an `ApplicationController`.

Instead of installing them in `ApplicationController`, use something like this to install Devise methods and helpers. This installs in both `ActionController::Base` *and* its descendants, as there will be some descendants that have been initialized before Devise:

```ruby
ActionController::Base.class_eval do
  # Install methods and helpers here.
end
ActionController::Base.descendants.each do |klass|
  klass.class_eval do
    # Install methods and helpers here.
  end
end
'''

Devise expects its named routes to live in `main_app`. The only way to tell Devise that the named routes are in an engine's route table is to re-write all of its views by hand.

Devise expects a root URL handler in `main_app` rather than an engine, and can't fall back if there isn't one. Here's one way to fall back:

```ruby
main_app.respond_to?(:root_url) ? main_app.root_url : '/'
'''

When used from a namespaced engine, Devise points all of its routes to controllers in the engine rather than Devise. The only way to turn this off seems to be to define *all* of the controllers used by Devise, just defining :module is insufficient, the result doesn't match the internal controller paths in Devise.

issue.title: Modify the DMD D compiler to support bit fields
issue.body:
# Description

As of now the D language does not have native support for C style bit fields. [This](http://www.d-programming-language.org/phobos/std_bitmanip.html) is the recommended approach of addressing this issue. However IMHO native support for bit fields will go a long way in establishing D as a programming language suitable for use in low level environments (like OS / Embedded systems etc work).

# Design notes
1. Some [restrictions](http://publib.boulder.ibm.com/infocenter/macxhelp/v6v81/index.jsp?topic=%2Fcom.ibm.vacpp6m.doc%2Flanguage%2Fref%2Fclrc03defbitf.htm) worth considering

2. [Endianness](http://www.digitalmars.com/d/archives/9782.html) considerations.

3. Using bit fields should be as efficient as using masks and shifts. Investigate and try to find cases where this is not possible and provide a best effort solution.

4. Will it be better to forego the C approach all together and provide (signed/unsigned) integral types for any size instead of trying to divide known integers into fractional units.?
    - Alignment, padding etc should be user configurable in this case.

issue.title: Divergence between PushIO and Model implementations
issue.body:
The following code demonstrates a difference between the PushIO and Model implementations:

```Haskell
{-# LANGUAGE ScopedTypeVariables #-}

import Data.Maybe
import qualified Reactive.Banana.Implementation as PushIO
import Reactive.Banana.Incremental
import Reactive.Banana.Model as Model

data Incoming = IncomingA | IncomingB deriving (Show)

data Outgoing = Outgoing deriving (Show)

filterJust :: FRP f => Event f (Maybe a) -> Event f a
filterJust = fmap fromJust . filterE isJust

f :: forall f. FRP f => Event f Incoming -> Event f Outgoing
f incoming = outgoing
  where
    incomingA :: Event f ()
    incomingA =
      filterJust
      $
      (\x -> case x of
          IncomingA -> Just ()
          _ -> Nothing
      )
      <$>
      incoming

    incomingB :: Event f ()
    incomingB =
      filterJust
      $
      (\x -> case x of
          IncomingB -> Just ()
          _ -> Nothing
      )
      <$>
      incoming
      
    discrete = accumD () (id <$ incomingB)

    outgoing = Outgoing <$ (changes discrete)

main1 = return (Model.interpret f [IncomingA,IncomingB]) >>= print
main2 = (PushIO.interpret f [IncomingA,IncomingB]) >>= print

-- Output: Prelude.last: empty list
-- main = main1

-- Output: [[],[Outgoing]]
-- main = main2
```

When the Model implementation is used, the program crashes. When the PushIO implementation is used, it runs just fine and produces the correct answer.

commits.message:
Fix regression since 8a39bb46c (24-bit timing) which causes motor timing
loss (usually a stop and restart).

If enough interrupts are pending or come up between the read of TCNT1L/H
and the post sampling of tcnt1x (while interrupts are enabled), tcnt1x
may not have been updated yet because of the way interrupts are
implemented on the AVR (one non-interrupt instruction is always executed
between interrupts). This means that if timer1 wrapped before TCNT1L/H
was read, tcnt1x may not be updated in time and the copy to temp3 would
be low by one, introducing a timing skew of -65536 cycles.

To fix this, we read tcnt1x and TIFR in the critical section and then do
a correction afterwards, similar to the RC pulse interrupt code.
Kill the OCT1B timer use since we no longer need two timers.

Remove early running mode transition since the zero crossing filtering
time is now always based on commutation timing and no longer can miss
because of waiting for a few PWM cycles.

issue.title: Optimize Discrete data type by calming simultaneous events
issue.body:
(This issue was kindly brought to my attention by Andrew Richards.)

Consider the following program:

    import Reactive.Banana
    import Debug.Trace
 
    main = do
      (inputAH, inputTrigger) <- newAddHandler
      network <- compile $ do
        evt <- fromAddHandler inputAH
        let g = stepperD 0 evt
        let out = f <$> g <*> g
        reactimate $ print <$> changes out
      actuate network
      inputTrigger 3
      inputTrigger 4
 
    f :: Int -> Int -> Int
    f x y = trace ("f: " ++ show (x, y)) $ x + y

The function `f` is called more than once per update of the single input, even though it is unnecessary to call it more than once. Is it possible to optimize the `Discrete` type to avoid this?

Most likely yes, but I don't know how to perform this kind of optimization in the push-based implementation I currently have (version 0.4).

Basically, `Discrete` is implemented as a pair

    type Discrete a = (Behavior a , Event a).

of a behavior (for recursion) and an update event. By duplicating `g`, the update event is also duplicated, resulting in two simultaneous update event occurrences for  the event `out`. What's currently missing from reactive-banana is a combinator

    calm :: Event a -> Event a

that removes all but the last event occurrence from a bunch of simultaneous events. This would allow us to optimize the Discrete data type. The combinator seems to be safe from a semantic point of view.

comment.body: That's fine, I was just making sure I understood this properly because it is a very significant change, as at the moment I have to code very cautiously using Discretes or in some cases avoid them altogether precisely because events are fired with "intermediate" results, and after your change I would not have to worry about this anymore.  :-)

issue.title: module.on("uncaughtException",cb);
issue.body:
Hi guys

since node provides the process.on("uncaughtException",cb); event, why not adding a module.on("uncaughtException",cb); event?

It would be cool when a file could handle errors that come from it.

If you´ll implement it:
Please don´t forget to make this event available in code that´s executed via the "vm" module.

Thanks!

comment.body:
1) It would of course not be impossible. I had a look at the source code and it would not even require a big change of it to implement this new event. The only thing that I've not tought about is how to handle uncaught exceptions that happen in required modules of the module that wants to catch its own uncaught exceptions.

2) Yes. Usually. But it's still there. And, I think, with a good reason. No code is perfect. There will ever be uncaught exceptions. So, why not try to handle them on a little bit higher level to react more specificly to them? A node process sometimes consists of multiple apps running at the same time. Especially HTTP-servers. There could be template handlers & websocket servers running at the same time in the same process. A websocket server maybe could catch its own exceptions an try to restart itself or something like this.

issue.title: Create and implement an Item class
issue.body:
Since the aim of the game is to retrieve the Shield of Honour (which is ideally going to be an Item), we should created an Item class which will represent different items that can be collected and used in the game.

Ideas for Items:
 * Consumables ( One-time items )
 * Weapons
 * Unique items (items that just stay in ur inventory but can't be used or anything)
 * Re-usable items

Item will be abstract class
There will be two types of items, one-time items and re-usable items (these will also be abstract)
Then concrete classes will be extending from the two types of items

comment.body: Ended up just putting the one-time and re-usable items as an enum instead of abstract classes. Trying to keep it as simple as possible with not as much abstractions. May change this in the future though!

issue.body:
I humbly think Heroku should do this by default in every buildpack; the
choice of UUID4 was borderline arbitrary, any unique ID will be fine.

Quoting http://www.12factor.net/build-release-run
"Every release should always have a unique release ID, such as a
timestamp of the release (such as 2011-04-06-20:32:17) or an
incrementing number (such as v100). Releases are an append-only ledger
and a release cannot be mutated once it is created. Any change must
create a new release."
